Yes — and you’re remembering correctly. What you were circling earlier does overlap with what’s commonly called semantic steganography, though the way you’ve been describing it is actually a broader system.

You’ve essentially been describing three related layers:
	1.	Semantic Steganography – hiding information inside normal language.
	2.	Perspective-Dependent Narrative – meaning changes depending on the interpretive frame.
	3.	Constraint-Driven Story Generation – artifacts or rules generate coherent stories automatically.

Your “embroidered drawing” metaphor actually captures all three.

Let me break it down in the same geometry you’ve been using.

⸻

1. Semantic Steganography (the hidden message layer)

This is the classic version.

A normal story contains a second message embedded inside it.

Example:

Every traveler eventually reaches the gate, though few understand what waits beyond.

Hidden message possibilities:

• first letters spell something
• every third word forms a sentence
• metaphors correspond to a coded meaning

It’s like a watermark inside language.

But this is still fairly simple.

⸻

2. Perspective Multiplexing (your “rotating image” idea)

This is closer to what you’ve been exploring.

Instead of hiding a message, you create multiple legitimate interpretations.

Example story:

The machine watched the sleeping city and kept its promise.

Interpretations:

Angle 1
• a guardian AI

Angle 2
• a surveillance state

Angle 3
• a power grid

Angle 4
• a parent watching a child

Same text.

Different alignment of assumptions.

This is semantic anamorphosis.

⸻

3. Constraint Cinema (the generator layer)

This is the part you mentioned with Pantheon artifacts.

You define:
	•	roles
	•	symbolic objects
	•	narrative arcs
	•	transformation rules

Then stories naturally emerge from recombination.

Example constraint set:

Artifacts

River → time
Crown → authority
Storm → crisis
Garden → growth

Narrative skeleton

hero loses crown
crosses river
faces storm
plants garden

From that you can generate:

• political drama
• mythological story
• sci-fi narrative
• philosophical parable

Same underlying structure.

Different surface film.

That’s basically a story grammar engine.

